  "@type": "Article",
  "description": "I\u0026rsquo;m thinking about different facets of why, in American idiom, post- is often interpreted as meaning anti- rather than \u0026ldquo;after\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;beyond\u0026rdquo;.\n¶Basic idea ¶Linguistics In English language, \u0026ldquo;post-\u0026rdquo; has historically, and in dictionaries, just meant \u0026ldquo;after\u0026rdquo;: it\u0026rsquo;s a temporal condition, not an opposing relation: post-war, post-natal.\nBut in political and theoretical discourse, it often has connotations of \u0026ldquo;against\u0026rdquo;: postmodernism is seen as after modernism temporally and as rejecting the claims of modernism, usually specifically modernist universalism.\n",
  "name": "2025-09-28, 0826h, On american translation of 'post-' to 'anti-'",
